05639nam a2200697Ia 9781847425362DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20012001xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a9781847425362  a(DE-B1597)647303  a(OCoLC)1295312573  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aPOL0020002bisacsh04a363.5946094100aInclusive housing in an ageing society :bInnovative approaches /ced. by Sheila Peace, Caroline Holland. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of tables and figures -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes on contributors -- tHousing an ageing society -- tPolicy and technology debates -- tFrom ‘special needs’ to ‘lifestyle choices’: articulating the demand for ‘third age’ housing -- tLifetime Homes -- tThe politics of accessible housing in the UK -- tThe implications of smart home technologies -- tDementia and technology -- tNew lives for old? -- tIntegrated segregation? Issues from a range of housing/care environments -- tOlder people’s CoHousing Communities -- tRetirement communities in Britain: a ‘third way’ for the third age? -- tShaping everyday life: beyond design -- tInclusive housing -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe housing problems of older people in our society are highly topical because of the growing number of retired people in the population and, especially, the yet-to-come increasing number of 'very old' people. Government policies on the care of older people have been forthcoming from Whitehall, but the issue of housing is just beginning to be seriously addressed. This book represents a first attempt at bringing together people from the worlds of architecture, social science and housing studies to look at the future of living environments for an ageing society. Projecting thinking into the future, it asks critical questions and attempts to provide some of the answers. It uniquely moves beyond the issues of accommodation and care to look at the wider picture of how housing can reflect the social inclusion of people as they age. Inclusive housing in an ageing society will appeal to a wide audience - housing, health and social care workers including: housing officers, architects, planners and designers, community regeneration workers, care managers, social workers and social care assistants, registered managers and housing providers, health improvement staff and, of course, current and future generations of older people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aInclusionary housing programszGreat Britain. 0aOlder peoplexHousingzGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh1 aBernard, Miriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiggs, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrenton, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisk, Malcolm J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanson, Julienne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolland, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolland, Caroline, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKellaher, Leonie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKingston, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMadigan, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu